  "body": " Hilbert schemes of curves  Denote by the Hilbert scheme of curves of degree and genus in the projective space . By \"component\" we always mean an irreducible component.    Fix . Let be the open subscheme of the Hilbert scheme that parameterizes smooth curves. For each point , we define the Gauss map sending a point of to the tangent line at that point. Define Z^e:=\\{[C]\\in{\\rm Hilb}^{sm}_{d,g}(\\mathbb{P}^r)| \\textrm{ the Gauss map of the curve is inseparable of degree }\\}. Then .    What can we say about the set ? Can we construct exotic components (i.e. components that only exist in characteristic ) using this stratification? Study the action by the Galois group .    There are some other stratifications one may consider, e.g. the one obtained by the topological type of the ramification divisor.      Is the Hilbert scheme of local Cohen-Macaulay curves in connected?      Let be a family of curves in such that a general curve in this family is a smooth complete intersection, and the special curve is smooth.    Is always a complete intersection, assuming that the characteristic is 0?    If the characteristic is , the answer is negative; if , the answer is negative; if is not smooth, the answer is negative. The reference is [P. Ellia, R. Hartshorne, Smooth specializations of space curves: questions and examples , Commutative algebra and algebraic geometry (Ferrara), 53–79, Lecture Notes in Pure and Appl. Math., 206, Dekker, New York, 1999].      P. Ellia and R. Hartshorne    Let be an integral surface of degree with a double curve of degree , and triple points, pinch point, etc.    There exists such that for any smooth curve of degree , let be the irreducible component of the Hilbert scheme containing , then a general is also contained in a surface of degree and a double curve of degree .    The conjecture is posed in [P. Ellia, R. Hartshorne, Smooth specializations of space curves: questions and examples , Commutative algebra and algebraic geometry (Ferrara), 53–79, Lecture Notes in Pure and Appl. Math., 206, Dekker, New York, 1999]. It is proved to be true for in [J. Brevik, F. Mordasini, Curves on a ruled cubic surface , Collect. Math. 54 (2003), no. 3, 269–281].      Fix . Find a good\/sharp lower bound for the dimension of components of .    For a lower bound is ; for the lower bound is which is obviously not a good bound for fixed and sufficiently large.    In the range there is a better bound, c.f. [D. Chen, On the dimension of the Hilbert scheme of curves , Math. Res. Lett. 16 (2009), no. 6, 941–954. Theorem 1.3].      (1) Let be of bidegree on a nonsingular quadric surface in . Can be connected to an extremal curve in ? (2) Given skew lines on a nonsingular quadric in . Does there exists a family , and a family such that is locally Cohen-Macaulay?    (2) implies (1).      Fix . Let be an irreducible component.    What is the largest number of points in general position you can make these curves pass through?    This is a hard problem. If the curves are arithmetically Cohen-Macaulay, it should be treatable.      What is the best pair (in the vague sense that is as small as possible and is close to as possible) such that there is a component of whose general member has an embedded point.    An example of a pair satisfying the above condition is , , c.f. [D. Chen, S. Nollet, Detaching embedded points , ].     Hartshorne-Rao modules   The following three problems are related to the Hartshorne-Rao modules. Let be a projective space with homogeneous coordinate ring . Given a space curve with ideal sheaf , the Hartshorne-Rao module is defined as the -module . A program to study the Hilbert scheme of space curves of degree and genus is outlined in [M. Martin-Deschamps, D. Perrin, Sur la classification des courbes gauches. Astérisque No. 184-185 (1990), 208 pp.]. Namely, can be stratified into consisting of curves such that, for every , and have fixed dimensions and , respectively. Now let be the moduli space of finite length graded modules with Hilbert function . There is a natural map from to , and properties of can be extracted from properties of .    Let and define . For which is irreducible?    It is proved that if then is reducible ( [M. Martin-Deschamps, D. Perrin, Courbes gauches et modules de Rao , J. Reine Angew. Math. 439 (1993), 103–145. page 119, Theorem 2.1]). Conjecturally, if then is irreducible.      Describe the irreducible component of .      What do properties of the Rao modules imply about ? For example, if is Gorenstein or annihilated by a linear form, does have any nice properties?    We might have to require to be minimal.    "
